05214nam a22008535i 9780231527132DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2011    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315271327 a10.7312/robb156372doi  a(DE-B1597)459265  a(OCoLC)1013950088  a(OCoLC)1029835723  a(OCoLC)1032680212  a(OCoLC)1037976396  a(OCoLC)931998057  a(OCoLC)979909929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBR115.P7bR69 2015 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a261.72231 aRobbins, Jeffrey, eauthor.10aRadical Democracy and Political Theology /cJeffrey Robbins. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Radical Democracy -- t1. Democracy, More Or Less -- tInterlude. Managing Democracy Abroad -- t2. Democracy, Radically Conceived -- tPart Two. Political Theology -- t3. Political Theology and the Postsecular -- tInterlude. The Iranian Revolution Redux -- t4. Political Theology, Beyond Despair -- t5. Political Theologies, or Finding an Alternative to Schmitt -- t6. The Theopolitics of Democracy -- tConclusion. From the One to the Many -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlexis de Tocqueville once wrote that "the people reign over the American political world like God over the universe," unwittingly casting democracy as the political instantiation of the death of God. According to Jeffrey W. Robbins, Tocqueville's assessment remains an apt observation of modern democratic power, which does not rest with a sovereign authority but operates as a diffuse social force. By linking radical democratic theory to a contemporary fascination with political theology, Robbins envisions the modern experience of democracy as a social, cultural, and political force transforming the nature of sovereign power and political authority.Robbins joins his work with Michael Hardt and Antonio Negri's radical conception of "network power," as well as Sheldon Wolin's notion of "fugitive democracy," to fashion a political theology that captures modern democracy's social and cultural torment. This approach has profound implications not only for the nature of contemporary religious belief and practice but also for the reconceptualization of the proper relationship between religion and politics. Challenging the modern, liberal, and secular assumption of a neutral public space, Robbins conceives of a postsecular politics for contemporary society that inextricably links religion to the political.While effectively recasting the tradition of radical theology as a political theology, this book also develops a comprehensive critique of the political theology bequeathed by Carl Schmitt. It marks an original and visionary achievement by the scholar the Journal of the American Academy of Religion hailed "one of the best commentators on religion and postmodernism."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aDeath of God theologyxPolitical aspects. 0aDemocracyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aPolitical theology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/robb15637423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231527132.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package B